<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,732,1084]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,493,732,759]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Diagnosis of 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[321,337,732,746]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">rd</superScript>
instar larva.
</emphasis>
Head capsule with small ocular tubercles; mandibles bent upward in most genera; apical tooth longer than the other teeth; labial palpi four-articulated, segments 2â€“4 longer than the basal width of the mandible. Mesothoracic spiracles not raised on tubercle. Most genera are characterized by the presence of a median tuft of setae on the mesonotum. Thoracic setiferous processes pedunculated; abdominal series of setiferous processes sessile in most genera. VIII abdominal sternite without odontoid processes; IX abdominal sternite longer than wide, without rastra or fossoria.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,732,1084]" box="[199,1219,950,975]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,393,950,975]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Biological notes.</emphasis>
The larvae are ambush hunters able to move both forward and backward.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,732,1084]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,987,1012]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Comments.</emphasis>
The larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1899" box="[507,676,987,1012]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Dendroleontini">Dendroleontini</taxonomicName>
are poorly known and only few genera are sufficiently described. The members of this group often present peculiar specializations and extra-European taxa differ in the number of mandibular teeth, presence of mesothoracic tuft of setae and development of abdominal setiferous processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
